Vice President Kamala Harris spoke at the Edmund Pettus Bridge in Selma, Alabama, commemorating the 57th anniversary of the march for voting rights. She highlighted the importance of the freedom to vote and the ongoing fight to protect it. Harris emphasized the need for federal voting rights legislation and urged the Senate not to allow an arcane rule to deny this right. She also called for the prevention of anti-voter laws and the defense of voting rights in court. Harris acknowledged the long-standing activists and leaders who have fought for voting rights and emphasized the importance of fighting for economic, social, and racial justice. She mentioned President Biden's historic nomination of Judge Ketanji Brown Jackson to the Supreme Court and the legacy of Congressman John Lewis, who was a prominent figure in the civil rights movement. Harris concluded by encouraging continued activism and determination in the pursuit of victory for voting rights.